<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,501]" pageId="3" pageNumber="223">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,455,151,176]" pageId="3" pageNumber="223">General morphology.</emphasis>
Encrusting sponge measuring 
<quantity box="[810,858,152,176]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="3" pageNumber="223" unit="cm" value="1.0">1cm</quantity>
de diameter, brown colour. Spicules. Megascleres slightly curved (
<number box="[343,446,188,213]" pageId="3" pageNumber="223" value="420.0" valueMax="468.0" valueMin="372.0">372–468</number>
/ 
<number box="[454,524,188,213]" pageId="3" pageNumber="223" value="41.5" valueMax="48.0" valueMin="35.0">35–48</number>
µm), robust, smooth strongyles (
<figureCitation box="[905,978,188,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1977,1999]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,1196,1956]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,1196,1956]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. Drulia cristata: (a, b) megasclere strongyles; (c, d) microsclere oxeas; (e) detail of gemmule surface with gemmuloscleres embedded. Scale bars: 50 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/242086/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="223">
Fig. 
<number box="[962,978,188,213]" pageId="3" pageNumber="223" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
a,b). Microscleres microspined straight, acanthoxeas (
<number box="[307,394,223,248]" pageId="3" pageNumber="223" value="100.5" valueMax="123.0" valueMin="78.0">78–123</number>
/ 
<number box="[403,445,223,248]" pageId="3" pageNumber="223" value="4.5" valueMax="6.0" valueMin="3.0">3–6</number>
µm), middle spines (
<number box="[685,727,223,248]" pageId="3" pageNumber="223" value="4.5" valueMax="6.0" valueMin="3.0">3–6</number>
µm) tapered (
<figureCitation box="[888,960,223,248]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1977,1999]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,1196,1956]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,1196,1956]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. Drulia cristata: (a, b) megasclere strongyles; (c, d) microsclere oxeas; (e) detail of gemmule surface with gemmuloscleres embedded. Scale bars: 50 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/242086/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="223">
Fig. 
<number box="[944,960,223,248]" pageId="3" pageNumber="223" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
c,d). Gemmules are hemispherical raging 
<number box="[151,251,260,285]" pageId="3" pageNumber="223" value="462.0" valueMax="540.0" valueMin="384.0">384–540</number>
µm in diameter (
<figureCitation box="[472,552,260,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1977,1999]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,1196,1956]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,1196,1956]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. Drulia cristata: (a, b) megasclere strongyles; (c, d) microsclere oxeas; (e) detail of gemmule surface with gemmuloscleres embedded. Scale bars: 50 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/242086/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="223">
Fig. 
<number box="[536,552,260,284]" pageId="3" pageNumber="223" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
e). Gemmular theca made by thin layer consisting of spongin, where gemmuloscleres are embedded tangentially (
<figureCitation box="[651,719,295,320]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1977,1999]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,1196,1956]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,1196,1956]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. Drulia cristata: (a, b) megasclere strongyles; (c, d) microsclere oxeas; (e) detail of gemmule surface with gemmuloscleres embedded. Scale bars: 50 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/242086/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="223">
Fig. 
<number box="[703,719,296,320]" pageId="3" pageNumber="223" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
e).
</paragraph>
